				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Hyp=
erbolic analogues of trigonometric functions</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"Hyperbolic =
curve" redirects here. For the geometric curve, see <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbola" title=3D"Hyperbola">Hyperbola</a>.</div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Sinh"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"C=
osh"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Tanh"></span><span class=3D"anchor=
" id=3D"Sech"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Csch"></span><span class=
=3D"anchor" id=3D"Coth"></span>
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Sinh_cosh_tanh.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://u=
pload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Sinh_cosh_tanh.svg/500px-S=
inh_cosh_tanh.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"333" height=3D"333" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"504" data-file-height=3D"504"></a>=
<figcaption></figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, <b>hyperbolic functions</b> are analogues of the or=
dinary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_function" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trigonometric function">trigonometric functions=
</a>, but defined using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperb=
ola" title=3D"Hyperbola">hyperbola</a> rather than the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circle</a>. Just as the point=
s <span class=3D"texhtml">(cos <i>t</i>, sin <i>t</i>)</span> form a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_circle" title=3D"Unit circle">circl=
e with a unit radius</a>, the points <span class=3D"texhtml">(cosh <i>t</i>=
, sinh <i>t</i>)</span> form the right half of the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Unit_hyperbola" title=3D"Unit hyperbola">unit hyperbola</a=
>. Also, similarly to how the derivatives of <span class=3D"texhtml">sin(<i=
>t</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">cos(<i>t</i>)</span> are <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml">cos(<i>t</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=80=93=
sin(<i>t</i>)</span> respectively, the derivatives of <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">sinh(<i>t</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">cosh(<i>t</i>)</span> =
are <span class=3D"texhtml">cosh(<i>t</i>)</span> and <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">sinh(<i>t</i>)</span> respectively.
</p><p>Hyperbolic functions are used to express the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Angle_of_parallelism" title=3D"Angle of parallelism">angl=
e of parallelism</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic=
_geometry" title=3D"Hyperbolic geometry">hyperbolic geometry</a>. They are =
used to express <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_boost" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lorentz boost">Lorentz boosts</a> as <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_rotation" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Hyperbolic rotation">hyperbolic rotations</a> in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity" title=3D"Special relativity">spe=
cial relativity</a>. They also occur in the solutions of many linear <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_equation" title=3D"Differen=
tial equation">differential equations</a> (such as the equation defining a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catenary" title=3D"Catenary">caten=
ary</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_equation#Hyperboli=
c_solution_for_one_real_root" title=3D"Cubic equation">cubic equations</a>,=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace%27s_equation" title=
=3D"Laplace's equation">Laplace's equation</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Carte=
sian coordinates">Cartesian coordinates</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Laplace%27s_equation" title=3D"Laplace's equation">Laplace's equ=
ations</a> are important in many areas of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>, including <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Electromagnetic theory">electromagnetic theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_transfer" title=3D"Heat transfer">heat transfer<=
/a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynamics" title=3D"=
Fluid dynamics">fluid dynamics</a>.
</p><p>The basic hyperbolic functions are:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_function=
s#cite_note-:1-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><b>hyperbolic sine</b> "<span class=3D"texhtml">sinh</span>" (<span=
 class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap"><span class=3D"IPA nopopups noexcerpt" l=
ang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English=
