/wiki/Unit_hyperbola" title=3D"Unit hyperbola">unit hyperbola</a> <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 <i>y</i><sup>2</sup> =3D 1</s=
pan> at the point <span class=3D"texhtml">(cosh <i>a</i>, sinh <i>a</i>)</s=
pan>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</sp=
an> is twice the area between the ray, the hyperbola, and the <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>-axis. For points on=
 the hyperbola below the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">x</span>-axis, the area is considered negative (see <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:HyperbolicAnimation.gif" title=3D"File:Hyper=
bolicAnimation.gif">animated version</a> with comparison with the trigonome=
tric (circular) functions).</figcaption></figure>
<p>The hyperbolic functions take an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Argument_of_a_function" title=3D"Argument of a function">argument</a> cal=
led a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_angle" title=3D"H=
yperbolic angle">hyperbolic angle</a>. The magnitude of a hyperbolic angle =
is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</=
a> of its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_sector" title=
=3D"Hyperbolic sector">hyperbolic sector</a> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
xy</i> =3D 1</span>. The hyperbolic functions may be defined in terms of th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_sector#Hyperbolic_tri=
angle" title=3D"Hyperbolic sector">legs of a right triangle</a> covering th=
is sector.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_analysis" title=
=3D"Complex analysis">complex analysis</a>, the hyperbolic functions arise =
when applying the ordinary sine and cosine functions to an imaginary angle.=
 The hyperbolic sine and the hyperbolic cosine are <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Entire_function" title=3D"Entire function">entire function=
s</a>. As a result, the other hyperbolic functions are <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meromorphic_function" title=3D"Meromorphic function">m=
eromorphic</a> in the whole complex plane.
</p><p>By <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lindemann%E2%80%93Weiers=
trass_theorem" title=3D"Lindemann=E2=80=93Weierstrass theorem">Lindemann=E2=
=80=93Weierstrass theorem</a>, the hyperbolic functions have a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendental_number" title=3D"Transcendental=
 number">transcendental value</a> for every non-zero <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_number" title=3D"Algebraic number">algebraic v=
alue</a> of the argument.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-12"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHyperbolic_functions&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The first known calculation of a hyperbolic trigonometry problem is attr=
ibuted to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerardus_Mercator" title=
=3D"Gerardus Mercator">Gerardus Mercator</a> when issuing the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercator_projection" title=3D"Mercator projecti=
on">Mercator map projection</a> circa 1566. It requires tabulating solution=
s to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendental_equation" ti=
tle=3D"Transcendental equation">transcendental equation</a> involving hyper=
bolic functions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:3-13"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>The first to suggest a similarity between the sector of the circle a=
nd that of the hyperbola was <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac=
_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Isaac Newton</a> in his 1687 <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophi%C3%A6_Naturalis_Principia_Mathematica=
" title=3D"Philosophi=C3=A6 Naturalis Principia Mathematica"><i>Principia M=
athematica</i></a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:0-14"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Cotes" title=3D"Roger=
 Cotes">Roger Cotes</a> suggested to modify the trigonometric functions usi=
ng the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary_unit" title=3D"Im=
aginary unit">imaginary unit</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-e=
lement-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" =
style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"=
 alttext=3D"{\displaystyle i=3D{\sqrt {-1}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>i</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle i=3D{\sqrt {-=
1}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/370c8cebe9634fbfc84c29ea61680b0ad4a1ae0d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:8.807ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle i=
=3D{\sqrt {-1}}}"></span> to obtain an oblate <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Spheroid" title=3D"Spheroid">spheroid</a> from a prolate one.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-:0_14-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:0-14"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Hyperbolic functions were formally introduced in 1757 by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vincenzo_Riccati" title=3D"Vincenzo Riccati">=
Vincenzo Riccati</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_14-2" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:0-14"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_13-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:3-13"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:4-15"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Riccati us=
ed <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>Sc.</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>Cc.</i></span> (<span title=3D"Latin-language text"><i lang=3D"la">sinus/c=
osinus circulare</i></span>) to refer to circular functions and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>Sh.</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>Ch.</i></span=
> (<span title=3D"Latin-language text"><i lang=3D"la">sinus/cosinus hyperbo=
lico</i></span>) to refer to hyperbolic functions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_14=
-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic=
_functions#cite_note-:0-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As early as 1759, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_Daviet_de_Foncenex" title=3D"Fran=C3=
=A7ois Daviet de Foncenex">Daviet de Foncenex</a> showed the interchangeabi=
lity of the trigonometric and hyperbolic functions using the imaginary unit=
 and extended <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Moivre%27s_formul=
a" title=3D"De Moivre's formula">de Moivre's formula</a> to hyperbolic func=
tions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:4-15"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-:0_14-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:0-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>During the 1760s, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johann_He=
inrich_Lambert" title=3D"Johann Heinrich Lambert">Johann Heinrich Lambert</=
a> systematized the use functions and provided exponential expressions in v=
arious publications.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_14-5" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:0-14"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_15-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-:4-15"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Lambert credited Riccati for the terminology and names of the functions, b=
ut altered the abbreviations to those used today.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_15-=
3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_=
functions#cite_note-:4-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_n=
ote-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
