<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Osborn"></span>
The hyperbolic functions satisfy many identities, all of them similar in fo=
rm to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_identity" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trigonometric identity">trigonometric identi=
ties</a>. In fact, <b>Osborn's rule</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Osborn,_1902_20-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_=
functions#cite_note-Osborn,_1902-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
0<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (named after <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Osborn_(mathematician)" title=3D"George =
Osborn (mathematician)">George Osborn</a>) states that one can convert any =
trigonometric identity (up to but not including sinhs or implied sinhs of 4=
th degree) for <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: =
none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\disp=
