<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Comparison_with_circular_fu=
nctions">Comparison with circular functions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHyperbolic_functions&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;=
section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Comparison with circular functions"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Circular_and_hyperbolic_angle=
.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/Circular_and_hyperbolic_angle.svg/330px-Circ=
ular_and_hyperbolic_angle.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=
=3D"300" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"700" data-file-height=
=3D"700"></a><figcaption>Circle and hyperbola tangent at <span class=3D"tex=
html">(1, 1)</span> display geometry of circular functions in terms of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sector_of_a_circle" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Sector of a circle">circular sector</a> area <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u</span> and hyperbolic functions =
depending on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_sector" ti=
tle=3D"Hyperbolic sector">hyperbolic sector</a> area <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u</span>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The hyperbolic functions represent an expansion of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometry" title=3D"Trigonometry">trigonometry</a> b=
eyond the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_function" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Circular function">circular functions</a>. Both t=
ypes depend on an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argument_of_a_fu=
nction" title=3D"Argument of a function">argument</a>, either <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angle">circular angle</a> or <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_angle" title=3D"Hyperboli=
c angle">hyperbolic angle</a>.
</p><p>Since the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_sector#A=
rea" title=3D"Circular sector">area of a circular sector</a> with radius <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> and angle =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u</span> (in radi=
ans) is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i><sup>2</sup><i>u</i>/2</span>, it w=
ill be equal to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u=
</span> when <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =3D <span class=3D"nowrap">=
=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top:1px solid; padding:0 0.1em;">2</span></s=
pan></span>. In the diagram, such a circle is tangent to the hyperbola <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>xy</i> =3D 1</span> at <span class=3D"texhtml">(1, 1=
)</span>. The yellow sector depicts an area and angle magnitude. Similarly,=
 the yellow and red regions together depict a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_sector" title=3D"Hyperbolic sector">hyperbolic secto=
r</a> with area corresponding to hyperbolic angle magnitude.
</p><p>The legs of the two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_t=
riangle" title=3D"Right triangle">right triangles</a> with <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypotenuse" title=3D"Hypotenuse">hypotenuse</a> on=
 the ray defining the angles are of length <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=88=9A=
<span style=3D"border-top:1px solid; padding:0 0.1em;">2</span></span> time=
s the circular and hyperbolic functions.
</p><p>The hyperbolic angle is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Invariant_measure" title=3D"Invariant measure">invariant measure</a> with r=
espect to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squeeze_mapping" tit=
le=3D"Squeeze mapping">squeeze mapping</a>, just as the circular angle is i=
nvariant under rotation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_functions#cite_note-25"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gudermannian_function" =
title=3D"Gudermannian function">Gudermannian function</a> gives a direct re=
lationship between the circular functions and the hyperbolic functions that=
 does not involve complex numbers.
</p><p>The graph of the function <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-math=
ml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"htt=
p://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle a\cosh(x/a)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mi>cosh</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle a\cosh(x/a)}<=
/annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/1641ec0501b716d9ad8a43c5701c1e96dc7a5036" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:11.552ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle a\=
cosh(x/a)}"></span>=E2=81=A0</span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Catenary" title=3D"Catenary">catenary</a>, the curve formed by a u=
niform flexible chain, hanging freely between two fixed points under unifor=
m gravity.
</p>
